Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-line entry point that delegates to the precedence ladder. Lowest
precedence (ternary) is the top of the ladder; each tier increases in
binding strength down to primary expressions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse expression (entry point for expression parsing)

    Return proc parse_assignment_expression with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
Assignment is Java's lowest-precedence, RIGHT-associative operator family
(=, +=, -=, *=, /=, %=, &=, |=, ^=, <<=, >>=, >>>=). The left-hand side is
parsed as a full conditional (ternary) expression - which subsumes the
postfix/primary forms that can legally be an lvalue (identifier, field access,
array access). If an assignment operator follows, the right-hand side recurses
back into parse_assignment_expression to obtain right associativity
(a = b = c parses as a = (b = c)). The operator token is stored in the node's
value slot; the lowering maps it to the corresponding HIR operator.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_assignment_expression" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Single-identifier lambda form: 'x -> body'. Java's grammar permits an
    Note: unparenthesized single inferred-type parameter, which is indistinguishable
    Note: from an ordinary identifier expression until the '->' following it is seen.
    Note: A one-token save/restore lookahead peeks past the identifier: if the next
    Note: token is '->', this is a lambda and is parsed directly; otherwise the
    Note: snapshot is restored and the normal expression path runs unchanged. The
    Note: parenthesized forms ((x) -> ..., (int a) -> ...) are handled deeper in the
    Note: primary expression via parse_lambda_or_grouped.
